Job Profile
AAPS Salaried - Information Systems and Technology, Level C
Job Title
Manager, Data Systems and Analysis
Department
Communication and Strategic Initiatives | Dean's Office, Faculty of Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies
Compensation Range
5,906.25 - $8,508.42 CAD Monthly
Posting End Date
March 15, 2022
Note: Applications will be accepted until 11:59 PM on the day prior to the Posting End Date above.
Job End Date
Please provide a cover letter as part of your application as applications without a cover letter will not be considered.
Job Summary

Provides senior level data analysis, reporting and institutional research for the Faculty of Graduate & Postdoctoral Studies (G+PS), graduate program offices and external audiences, in aid of planning, policy formulation, and decision-making activities related to graduate education and postdoctoral fellows. Responsible for designing and delivering solutions to meet needs of G+PS and the University for data management and reporting operations across the graduate student lifecycle from admission, enrolment and progression to graduation and beyond; Manages data collection, integrity, storage, quality and analysis for the Faculty; Ensures data integrity and privacy compliance; Designs and programs data management applications for specific user groups. Plays a key role in defining a modern approach to data management as UBC transitions to a new student information system. Requires the ability to solve complex problems, to co-ordinate the activities of others, and to communicate effectively both in speech and in writing.


Organizational Status

Professional team member of the Communications and Strategic Initiatives (CASI) group within the Dean’s Office in the Faculty of Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies. Reports to the Assistant Dean, Strategic Technologies and Business Initiatives, and works closely with the Dean and Vice-Provost and the Faculty Executive Committee. Liaises with team leads/managers as necessary on their data needs. Works with Statscan, U15, provincial and government agencies where appropriate as a representative of G+PS. Participates in committees and working groups as a representative of G+PS, such as the Workday Student related groups, e.g. Academic Model or UBC Data Model committees. Liaises with IT Services, Enrolment Services, Planning and Institutional Research (PAIR), and other units on campus where G+PS is required to provide input on data management and systems development.


Work Performed
This position requires a broad data skill set and performs tasks associated with the entire data life cycle, from architecting, collecting, cleaning, analyzing, visualizing, to reporting and distributing data in order to deliver meaningful information for decision-making and reporting. This position is responsible for serving as the authoritative source for admissions and enrolment data for graduate students at UBC and conducts studies such as times to completion, outcome tracking, financial support analysis. Assesses needs, and creates applications for operational use and display of data.

Strategic planning and reporting vision (10%)
Develops a long-term roadmap for integrated reporting across various systems in collaboration with UBC data governance group to enable 360-degree reporting from first point of student contact to graduation and career success;
Establishes solutions for data merging and data enhancement across sources/systems to generate meaningful business insights;
Consults with university units, in particular graduate program offices and faculties, other administrative units, with respect to their information requirements.
Contributes to and evaluates technological solutions to meet data and reporting needs, both at UBC as a whole and within G+PS and the graduate ecosystem;
Gathers requirements on reports needed by graduate programs and Postdoctoral Fellows Office (PDFO) and evaluates feasibility to deliver self-service data reporting.
Data systems management and operations (40%)
Supports transition of all current reports (ad hoc, strategic) from HR/Finance/SIS to Workday;
Works with various teams (ecosystem, admissions, financial) on data definitions and reports;
Oversees all aspects of data management project conception, including database design, development, modeling, implementation, maintenance, and administration, ensuring integrity, quality and security;
Develops custom applications for the operational use of data including programming, structured design reviews, code reviews, and testing;
Identifies and troubleshoots database design, programming and technical problems of custom databases and applications used in Faculty operations;
Provides technical opinions on suitability of techniques and methodology for data collection and management;
Performs quality assurance testing; conducting post-implementation reviews to ensure continuous improvement and learning;
Establishes priorities for ongoing enhancements to databases and applications used by the Faculty;
Provides advice to and consults with Enrolment Services and IT Services on complex systems/data issues related to Graduate Studies;
Investigates, analyzes, and keeps current with data systems and management trends;
Occasionally advises G+PS unit managers on and troubleshoots systems programming issues;
May occasionally be called on to serve as intermediary between G+PS unit managers and Enrolment Services where enhanced technical communication is required to communicate a business need;
Occasionally supervises temporary student or professional staff who work on data analysis and communications projects.
Statistical analysis, surveys, and communications (40%)
Plans, designs, develops, and implements analytical reports, research projects, and statistical information on graduate admissions, enrolment, benchmarking and performance indicators, including analysis and reporting of UBC-specific data obtained from national benchmarking surveys;
Manages all aspects of research studies, including designing questionnaires, determining samples, collecting, organizing, synthesizing and analyzing data, monitoring returns, and reporting results;
Translates policy issues and/or problem areas into meaningful research studies;
Provides data to inform policy and resolution of issues in various content areas;
Develops and maintains web-based data dashboards and other visualization strategies to facilitate effective access to and communication of graduate education-related data;
Maintains common datasets and metadata in various applications, such as program, country, and organizational structure in the application system in sync with ISO standards and UBC data standards;
Responds to requests from units for data reports and reporting tools;
Provides data for campus-wide data metrics and benchmarking projects;
Identifies data quality standards and performs quality assurance testing;
Acts as liaison with other departments and government agencies regarding data acquisition, analysis and reporting;
Data/records security, privacy and planning (5%)
Responsible for ensuring the Faculty’s compliance with University policies on data security, privacy, retention and appropriate use;
Leads occasional internal audits of data security;
Provides training and advising to G+PS staff on appropriate data use and security;
Participates in campus-wide strategic planning on data systems, usage and warehousing;
Other related duties as required (5%)


Consequence of Error/Judgement

The results of data analysis, reports and research will be used in formulating policy, making decisions relating to the future of graduate education at the university, and evaluating the effectiveness of programs and policies and assist in data driven decision making for resource allocation. Hence errors in design, interpretation or analysis of research could have far reaching consequences. The validity of these decisions is therefore dependent upon comparability, reliability, statistical significance, representation, corroboration, and construct validity of the survey research. Errors could result in inefficient resource allocation, the continuation of poor practices, poor advice to administrators, reputational risks, and have adverse effects on morale and public relations. Any errors and/or omissions in judgment could seriously undermine the roles, responsibilities and effectiveness of The Dean and/or G+PS. Errors in the maintenance of compliance with data security and privacy policies could lead to data breaches which could compromise the privacy of past and current graduate students and postdoctoral fellows, and the integrity and trustworthiness of G+PS and UBC.


Supervision Received

Reports to the Assistant Dean, Strategic Technologies and Business Initiatives and receives direction as well from the Dean and Vice-Provost, Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies. Works with wide latitude. Work is reviewed in terms of achievement of high professional standards in the delivery of data and statistical analysis services and broad project objectives and goals. Project work determined in consultation with Associate and Assistant Deans.


Supervision Given

Occasionally supervises temporary student or professional staff who work on data analysis and communications projects for the Faculty.


Minimum Qualifications

Undergraduate degree in a relevant discipline. Minimum of three years of related experience, or the equivalent combination of education and experience.


Preferred Qualifications
University degree (master’s preferred) in Economics, Statistics, Data Management, or Business Management/MIS.
Extensive experience designing, developing, implementing, and managing database applications.
Extensive experience analyzing data and providing reports on statistical issues.
Expert knowledge required in Excel and Access, with knowledge in PowerPoint and Word an asset.
Expert SQL user.
Effective oral and written communication, analytical, interpersonal, and presentation skills.
Ability to exercise confidentiality and judgment.
Knowledge of Workday an asset
Skills and experience in management of data systems, including data warehouses/lakes, and analysis projects of moderate complexity.
Experience with common statistical and analytical tools such as PowerBI, Crystal Reports, Tableau, SPSS.
Experience with visualization tools, e.g. Tableau, d3, or R.
Ability to work effectively and diplomatically with a wide range of individuals at all organizational levels.
Ability to work both independently and within a team environment.
High level of technical expertise and attention to detail.
Ability to multi-task and work in a fast-paced environment.
Ability to work under pressure in time sensitive, mission critical situations.

Requisition ID: 144966

Join a purpose driven winning team, committed to results, in an inclusive and high-performing culture.
Purpose
Provide analytical support to the International Treasury team to facilitate effective governance over the International Treasuries on key topics such as Interest Rate Risk management, liquidity risk management, investments and FX hedging.
Accountabilities
1. Work on development and implementation of balance sheet analytics related to,
Modelling non-maturity deposits;
Calibrating mortgage prepayment rate;
Modelling term deposits with early redemptions
2. Develop tools and work on analysis related to,
Interest Rate Risk i.e. simulation of balance sheet and interest rate movements;
Liquidity risk and metrics such as Liquidity Coverage Ratio;
Management reporting: Develop, implement and produce periodic / ad-hoc reports
3. Ensure alignment of ALM methodology, measurement and policies
Work closely and coordinate on topics such as balance sheet management, risk limits, key exposures, regulatory initiatives etc.
Participate and work on regulatory initiatives such as IRRBB and FRTB while working with GRM and Treasury.
Review ALM related policies for different countries and update the International Treasury guidelines.
Participate in certain country-level Asset Liability Committees.
4. Maintain working relationships with internal stakeholders such as local Treasury teams and the relevant support functions.
Skills, Experiences and Functional Competencies
Experience with data ETL using Python and SQL is required;
Experience building, maintaining and administering a SQL database required;
Experience developing Business Intelligence tools in Python (i.e. Dash) required;
Solid knowledge of Financial Products including money markets and derivatives is desirable;
Familiarity with the relevant regulations i.e. RDARR, IRRBB, FRTB, Volcker is an asset;
Understanding of the Scotiabank operations and Finance systems (OBI) is an asset;
Self-driven, analytical and collaborative;
Ability to speak Spanish is an asset;
Education and Other Requirements
Undergraduate in Business, Finance or Accounting;
CFA / FRM designations is desirable
Location(s): Canada : Ontario : Toronto

